{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600647/1930073101/0717.xml":{"full_text":"B-8\nLIGHTNING IGNITES\nWESTERN TIMBER\nHundreds Fight Flames in\nTinder-Dry Woods of Idaho\nand Montana.\ni\nthe Associated Press.\nMISSOULI. Mont., July 31.\u2014Several\nhundred volunteers today were fighting\nflamrs in Western Montana and North\nern Idaho forests where lightning had\nIgnited the tinder-dry woods.\nA fire, sweeping along a six-mile front\nIn the Selway forest east of Kooskia,\nIdaho, last night had consumed 600\nacre\u00ae of timber. Another forest blaze\n60 miles northeast of Missoula rag?d be\nyond control. Two other less dangerous\nblazes were burning in the same region.\nSeveral fires were beyond control in\nthe Bitter Root Valley south of Conner.\nAnother was burning on Skalkaho Creek.\nTwenty-eight men and a string of\npack horses were sent to the Powell\nranger station, across the Bitter Root\nrange in Idaho. The men hiked 15\nmiles through difficult passes to fight\nthe advance of two fires In that see tor.\nRegional forest officials described\ncondition of the woods as similar to\nthat prior to the long seasons of de\nstructive forest fires in 1923.\nBOSTON ELKS\u2019 LODGE\nPLEADS BANKRUPTCY\nThree Receivers Appointed to Con\ntinue Hotel Business in Action\nBrought by Bank.\nBy the Associated Press.\nBOSTON. July 31.\u2014The Boston\nLodge of Elks, whose charter was sus\npended several months ago by the na\ntional organization for liquor law viola\ntion, is banlrrupt, John F. Malley. for\nmer grand exalted ruler, admitted yes\nterday In Suffolk County Court.\nMalley was appearing as counsel for\nthe local lodge before Judge Lummus in\nconnection with the petition of the First\nNational Bank of Boston for the ap-\nE ointment of a receiver to take over the\notel property, because it is in arrears\n\u00a9f its payments.\nHe told the court the lodge probably\nwould have gone into bankruptcy were\nHot the officers and members deeply\nconcerned about their second-mortgage\nbondholders and other creditors.\nMallev said the lodge had no business\nIn the hotel field and said that venture\nhad been a failure. The lodge is one\nof the largest in the country, and its\nnew home, erected several years ago in\nthe downtown theatrical section of the\nCity, combines a good sized hotel prop\nerty with the lodge rooms and a group\nof ground-floor retail stores.\nJudge Lummus appointed three re\nceivers. who were authorized to con\ntinue the hotel business, but under\nsome other name which will not Include\nthe word Elks\u201d or any derivative of It.\nSECRETARY WXINYAPI\nRULES WAR DEPARTMENT\nSioux Indians Confer Honors Upon\nHurled', and Bodenhamer,\nLegion Commander.\nBy the Associated Press.\nBISMARCK. N. Dak, July 31\u2014An\nother name for Patrick J. Hurley,\nSecretary of War, is \u201cWxinyapl.\u2019\u2019\nThe name, meaning \u201cfaithful,\u201d was\nConferred on the \u201cWar Secretary Tues\nday by Sioux Indians at a ceremony In\nconnection with the State convention\nOs the American Legion.\nO. L. Bodenhamer, national com\nmander of the Legion, was named\n\u201cMarplya -Kinyanyapi,\u201d which means\n\"fiving cloud.\u201d\nThe bonnet of feathers which went\nto Secretary Hurley with the new name\nwas presented by Chief Red Toma\nhawk. reputed to have been the man\nWho killed Sitting Bull.\nAGREE ON EQUIPMENT\nWill Hays Says Dispute Over Pat\nent Rights Is Settled.\nNEW YORK, July 31 (\u00a3>).\u2014'Will H.\nHays, president of the Motion Picture\nProducers and Distributors of America,\nInc., who has been in Parts as chair\nman of a conference between German\nand American motion and sound picture\npatent holders, returned Tuesday aboard\nthe lie de France.\nMr. Hays said disputes over patent\nrights held in America and Germany\nhad been settled and an exchange of\nequipment agreed upon.\n\"The agreement, I am confident, will\nOpen a new era of co-operation In the\ntechnical progress of the art,\u201d he said.\n\nSoviet Develop* Hunting;.\nMOSCOW A \u00bbl.\u2014To attract big game\nhunters to the Soviet Union, the state\ntourist bureau has undertaken to or\nganize special hunting trips to the\nSiberian forests and to various moun\ntain regions. Each group will be pro\nvided with a guide and interpreter.\nI SHORTEST WAY\nTO\nPITTSBURGH\nDETROIT\nA Connections\nto A>l Points\n\u201cTHE DIRECT\nW WAY FARES\u201d\nH FARES\nt V One Round\n\u25a09l Way Trip\nHagerstown $3 00 $5.40\nCumberland S.OO 9.00\nr*' Uniontown 6.00 10.80\nPittsburgh 7.00 12.60\n\u25a0iy Fairmont 6.35 11.45\nMorgantown 6.20 11.15\nClarkaburg 680 12.25\nWheeling 6.80 12.25\nCanton 9.35 16.85\nAkron 9 65 17.65\nToledo 12.50 22.50\nH Detroit 13 00 23.40\nBLUE RIDGE TRANS. CO.\n\u2022\u2022A BLUE RIDGE LINE\u201d\nUNITED BUS TERMINAL\nJ2th a Pe\u00abna. Ave. N.W. Phone Nat. 9711\nSWEET POTATO \u201cCLOTHES\u201d DUE\nFROM U. S. EXPERTS' RESEARCH\nSouth May Be Enriched if Tests Prove\nCrop Can Yield Starch for\nTextile Industry.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, July 31.\u2014Clothes con- j\ntaining a dash of American aweet po\ntato are next on the list of prospective\nscientific wonders.\nUnited States Bureau of Standard re\nsearches, which'aim to put sweet pota\ntoes and other Southern agricultural\ncrops into the textile industry and\nboost the Southern pine as a source of\npaper, were announced yesterday by\nTheodore Swann of Birmingham, Ala.,\nvice chairman of the Alabama Indus\ntrial Development Board.\nThe bureau begins work next month\non both projects, co-operating with I\nAlabama Polytechnic Institute for tex\no Because of Lowered Prices\u2014-This Year Our Greatest\na <xha n s weep sale\ny r I year Clean Sweep means more than a clearance of our own stocks. This year\nthe manufacturers themselves are cleaning house so as to have their own stocks in\norder for the anticipated business revival eagerly expected this Fall. i^>i\nleading manufacturers and wholesalers are using the facilities of Th